{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b8fd5765-778a-485c-9f7c-1dfadefe9c07","content":"\n\n## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Start the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a built DLL:\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector launches your server as a child process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Use the tabs** to:\n- **Tools** — list and invoke your tools with test inputs\n- **Resources / Prompts** — test those if exposed\n- **Notifications** — see server events\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Don't write to stdout** in your server for logging — it corrupts the MCP protocol. Use `stderr` for diagnostics (`Console.Error.WriteLine()`).\n- If your server needs **environment variables**, add them in the Inspector's \"Environment Variables\" section.\n- If using `launchSettings.json` or specific profiles, point the command at the built binary instead of `dotnet run`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e623c7a7-22fb-4bd1-9194-d796a9a88273","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":387},"id":"265adfe1-46fd-441f-b7cc-7153801d1339","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:22.553Z","parentId":"2bcdd454-ccd6-4df5-aea2-e8259b5606e5"}
